However, over the past decades, the overuse and misuse of antibiotics in medical treatment as well as breeding areas, led to the increasing emergence of multi-drug resistant (MDR) pathogens, which have become a severe threat to human health. Therefore, discovery of novel antibiotics is an extremely urgent task (Gootz 2010). Deepsea-derived actinomycetes,

living in the extreme environments such as high pressure, low temperature as well as poor nutrient, are considered to be a rich source for structurally novel and biologically active natural products (Gerwick and Moore In our efforts to discover new 2012; Subramani and William 2012; Luo et al. 2016). (cid:1) 2019 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group ABSTRACT A new (1, grincamycin L) and two known (2 and 3) angucycline derivatives were obtained from the fermentation of deepsea- derived Streptomyces lusitanus OUCT16-27 strain. The structures of 1–3 were elucidated based on the LC-MS analysis together with 1D and 2D NMR data assignment. In the antibacterial assay, 1 and 2 exhibited moderate growth inhibitions against multi-drug resistant (MDR) strains of E. faecium, E. faecalis and S. aureus with the minimum inhibitory concentrations (MICs) of 3.12–6.25 mg/mL. antibiotics from deepsea actinomycetes, the strain OUCT16-27 that exhibited moderate (inhibition zone: 10 (cid:1) 16 mm) inhibitory activities against MDR bacterial attracted our attention. This strain was isolated from the sediment of Indian Ocean (4495 m depth) and identified as Streptomyces lusitanus based on the 16 s rDNA sequence analysis (Supplementary Figure S1), from which species a variety of second- ary metabolites have been reported (Gould et al. 1993; Han et al. 2012; Lai et al. 2017; Huang et al. 2012; Zhu et al. 2017). In this study, we isolated a new (1) and two known (2 and 3) angucycline derivatives (Figure 1) from the fermentation broth of the Streptomyces lusitanus OUCT16-27 strain. Here, we describe the isolation, structure elu- cidation as well as the biological evaluation of these three angucycline compounds. 2. Results and discussion The S. lusitanus OUCT16-27 strain was fermented in a large scale (8 L) and the culture broth was extracted with EtOAc. The crude extract was subsequently subjected to the reversed-phase open column fractionation, and was further purified by HPLC to afford compounds 1–3.

Compound 1 was isolated as an orange amorphous solid. The molecular formula of 1 was determined to be C31H36O12 on the basis of the HR-ESIMS data ([M þ H]þ at m/z 601.2307, calcd 601.2285). The structure of 1 was elucidated by 1D and 2D (COSY, HSQC, HMBC and NOESY) NMR spectroscopic analysis. H-8 (dH 7.80) to C-10a (dC 115.3) and C-6 (dC 137.6) revealed the presence of two aro- matic rings (Supplementary Figure S2a). The two downfielded quaternary carbons of C-1 (dC 161.1) and C-5 (dC 158.0) assigned two hydroxyl groups at C-1 and C-5. The 13C chemical shift values of C-9 (dC 187.3) and C-10 (dC 187.9) together with the HMBC correlations from H-4 to C-10 and from H-8 to C-9 revealed the formation of an anthraquinone skeleton. The HMBC correlations from H-15 (dH 1.12) to C-11 (dC 40.0), C-12 (dC 71.0) and C-13 (dC 46.7), from H-13 (dH 2.23, 2.27) to C-11, C-12 and the carb- oxyl carbon C-14 (dC 173.5) determined the 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid side chain moiety. Furthermore, the downfielded chemical shift value of C-12 compared to other aliphatic carbons in side chain proved it to be a hydroxylated carbon. The side chain moiety was linked to C-2 on the anthraquinone core, which was determined by the HMBC correlations from H-11 (dH 2.95, 2.89) to C-1, C-2 and C-3 (dC 139.6). The NMR data of the 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid side chain were very similar to those of the known vineomycinone B2 (Matsumoto et al. 1991; Kusumi et al. 2013), thus the absolute configuration of C-12 was determined as 12 R. Additionally, two 1H spin systems of H-10/H-20/H-30/H-40/H-50/H-60 and H-100/H-200/H-300/ H-400/H-500/H-600 in COSY spectrum together with the HMBC correlations from H-10 (dH 4.82) to C-50 (dC 74.8), from H-100 (dH 4.89) to C-500 (dC 69.8) and from H-40 (dH 3.08) to C-100 (dC 96.8) suggested the presence of a rhodinose-(1!4)-olivosyl unit. The HMBC correlations from H-10 (dH 4.82) to C-5, C-6, C-7 (dC 133.1) revealed that this disacchar- ide moiety was connected to C-6 of the anthraquinone core. The coupling constant values of anomeric proton H-10 (J ¼ 12 Hz) and H-100 (J ¼ 2.4 Hz) revealed the b and a linkage of each sugar moiety, respectively. The NOE correlations (Supplementary Figure S2b) of H-10/H-30, H-10/H-50, H-40/H-60 and H-400/H-600 determined the disacchar- ide moiety as a-L-rhodinose-(1!4)-b-D-olivose, which identical to that in saquayamy- cin K (Shaaban et al. 2012) . Thus, 1 was identified as a new vineomycinone B2-type angucycline, named grincamycin L. The 1H and 13C NMR chemical shifts of 1 were shown in Supplementary Table S1.

Compound 2 was purified as an orange amorphous solid. Its molecular formula was established to be C43H56O16 from the HR-ESIMS data ([M þ Na]þ at m/z 851.3460, calcd 851.3466). According to the NMR spectra of 2, it shared the same structure with that of 1 with additional two sugar moieties. The HMBC correlations from H-1000 (dH 5.14) to C-12 (dC 77.6) and from H-10000 (dH 4.82) to C-4000 (dC 74.8) suggested an O-glycosidic di- sugar unit connected to C-12. Finally, by comparison of NMR chemical shift values of 2 with the reported data, it was identified as himalomycin B (Maskey et al. 2003). Compound 3 was isolated as a brown amorphous solid. The HR-ESIMS data showed formula as C19H14O6 ([M þ H]þ at m/z 339.0861, calcd 339.0869). its molecular Comparison of the 1 D and 2 D NMR spectra of 3 with those of 1 revealed the absence of sugar moieties in 3. In addition, different from the structure of 1, the HMBC correla- tions from H-3 (dH 7.16) to C-4 (dC 162.2), C-11 (dC 43.6), C-2 (dC 152.0), C-1 (dC 128.7) and from H-13 (dH 2.94, 2.67) to C-14 (dC 195.8) and C-1 suggested the connections of C-11 to C-2 and C-14 to C-1 on the anthraquinone skeleton. The HMBC correlations from H-15 (dH 1.31) to C-11, C-12 (dC 71.0) and C-13 (dC 53.0) and from H-13 to car- bonyl carbon C-14, C-12 and C-11 suggested the six-membered carbocycle with a ketone group attached on the anthraquinone core, and the downfielded chemical shift of C-12 suggested the presence of a hydroxyl group. Thus, the structure of 3 was identified as rabelomycin, which was further confirmed by the reported data. (Rix et al. 2003; Kharel et al. 2010; Liu et al. 1970). The 1H and 13C NMR chemical shifts of 3 were shown in Supplementary Table S1.

In the evaluation for the inhibitory effects of the isolated angucycline derivatives (1–3) against MDR bacterial strains, compound 1, with an a-L-rhodinose-(1!4)-b-D-oli- vose on the anthraquinone core, exhibited moderate growth inhibition against E. fae- calis CCARM 5172, E. faecium CCARM 5203 and S. aureus CCARM 3090 with the MICs of 6.25, 3.12 and 6.25 mg/mL, respectively. Compound 2 showed good growth inhib- ition against E. faecium CCARM 5203 with the MIC of 6.25 mg/mL; while 3 had null activities against the five tested MDR strains up to 50 mg/mL (Table 1). Therefore, we suggested that the glycosylation may play an important role on the antibacterial activ- ities of angucycline-type compounds. 3.1. General experimental procedure The NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker Avance III 600 spectrometer at 298 K. Chemical shifts were reported with reference to the respective solvent peaks and residual solvent peaks (dH 2.50 and dc 39.5 ppm for DMSO-d6). The HR-ESIMS data were obtained on a Q-TOF Ultima Global GAA076 MS spectrometer. The CD spectra were recorded on a JASCO J-715 spectropolarimeter, using MeOH as a solvent. The UV spectra were measured on a Beckman DU640 spectrophotometer. High-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) was performed on an Agillent 1260 Infinity equipped with Diode Array Detector (DAD). The OD measurements were recorded on a Biotech Epoch2 microplate reader.

The actinomycete strain was isolated from the deepsea sediment collected under the 4495 m depth of Indian Ocean, which was stored at -80 (cid:3)C before being processed. The sediment sample was suspended in distilled water and diluted into three gra- dients 10(cid:4)1, 10(cid:4)2, 10(cid:4)3 g/mL. Then, the suspension containing diverse bacteria was inoculated on actinomycete culture medium plates at 30 (cid:3)C for 3 days (soluble starch 20 g/L, KNO3 1 g/L, K2HPO4 0.5 g/L, MgSO4(cid:5)7H2O 0.5 g/L, NaCl 0.5 g/L, FeSO4(cid:5)7H2O 0.01 g/L, agar 20 g/L, pH = 7.0). In radial diffusion antibacterial assay, the EtOAc extract (100 mg) of OUCT16-27 strain showed significant inhibitory activities against MDR strains (inhibition zone: 10–16 mm) (Supplementary Figure S12). The sequence of 16S ribosomal DNA confirmed the OUCT16-27 as a Streptomyces lusitanus (NBRC 13464 (T)) strain showing a homology of 99.72% (GeneBank No.MH532549). 3.3. Isolation and purification of the compounds

The OUCT16-27 strain was grown and maintained on the MS agar medium plates (soya flour 30 g/L, mannitol 20 g/L, agar 20 g/L) for sporulation. For each fermentation, the strain was inoculated into the 1 L Erlenmeyer flasks containing 200 mL of the cul- ture medium (10 g/L soluble starch, 20 g/L glucose, 4 g/L corn syrup, 10 g/L yeast extract, 3 g/L beef extract, 0.5 g/L MgSO4(cid:5)7H2O, 0.5 g/L KH2PO4, 2 g/L CaCO3, and 30 g/ L sea salt, pH = 7.0), and incubated at 30 (cid:3)C on a rotary shaker at 220 rpm for 6 days. The combined culture broth (8 L) was centrifuged to yield supernatant. Then, the supernatant was extracted with EtOAc, and the combined organic extracts were parti- tioned between 90% MeOH and n-hexane to yield two residues. The aqueous MeOH layer (2.3 g) was subjected to C18 open column chromatography with 20–100% MeOH to afford 12 fractions. The fr.7 was further purified by C18 semipreparative HPLC elut- ing with a liner gradient (60–70% CH3CN, 1.5 mL/min) to yield compound 1 (2.3 mg). The fr.8 (60% CH3CN, 1.5 mL/min) yielded compound 2 (2.2 mg) and the fr.4 (60% CH3CN, 1.5 mL/min) yielded compound 3 (3.8 mg). Grincamycin L (1): orange, amorphous solid;

To determine the MICs (minimum inhibitory concentrations) of compounds 1–3, the MDR bacterial strains of Enterococcus faecalis CCARM 5172, Enterococcus faecium CCARM 5203, Escherichia coli CCARM 1009, Salmonella typhimurium CCARM 8250, Staphylococcus aureus CCARM 3090 (Culture Collection of Antimicrobial Resistant Microbes, Seoul Women’s university of Korea) were grown overnight at 37 (cid:3)C in LB medium and diluted with the LB broth to 106 cfu/mL. In the 96-well plates, different concentrations of the sample solutions in MeOH (10 lL) were dispensed into 190 lL of the cell suspension. The LB broth was used as a blank. Tetracycline and kanamycin were used as positive controls, and methanol was used as a negative control. The growth of MDR strains was measured after 18 h of the incubation at 37 (cid:3)C on a micro- plate reader at the wavelength of 600 nm.
